05010nam a22005415i 9780774857031DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19861986xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748570317 a10.59962/97807748570312doi  a(DE-B1597)661516  a(OCoLC)1097092447  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHT127 ǂb G66 1986eb 7aPOL0020002bisacsh04a971/.009/7321 aGoldberg, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Myth of the North American City :bContinentalism Challenged /cJohn Mercer, Michael Goldberg. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[1986] 4c©1986  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables -- tCharts -- tPreface -- tOn Comparing American and Canadian Cities -- tValues and Culture: A Context for Comparing American and Canadian Cities -- tSocial and Demographic Structure in Canada and the United States -- tEconomic Organization and Economic Institutions in Canada and the United States: The Fuel for Urban Growth and Change -- tPolitical Structure, Culture and Institutions in Canada and the U.S. -- tUrban Form and Institutions in Canada and the United States -- tUrban Form and Social Characteristics -- tUrban Local Government: Structure and Finance -- tA Multivariate Approach to Metropolitan Differences -- tMaking Plain the Difference -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tSubject and Place Index -- tName Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe continuing tendency to "continentalize" Canadian issues has been particularly marked in the area of urban studies where United States-based research findings, methodologies, and attitudes have held sway. In this book, Goldberg and Mercer demonstrate that the label "North American City" as widely used is inappropriate and misleading in discussion of the distinctive Canadian urban environment. Examining such elements of the cultural context as mass values, social and demographic structures, the economy, and political institutions, they reveal salient differences between Canada and the United States. One of the most important of the many contextual differences is the strong collective sense in Canada which accepts more public intervention in social and economic matters in contrast to the American commitment to individualism. Canadians, consequently, expect a livable central city which is compact and well-served by public transit and which has a fiscally sound local government. To demonstrate these issues, the discussion includes a detailed cross-national empirical analysis of over 300 North American metropolitan areas along some three dozen dimensions, including density, transportation, household change and structure, income and fiscal disparities, and economic structure. Since much urban planning in Canada is based upon the continentalist assumption, this volume should generate a reassessment of policy and encourage the development of a research base to suit the distinctiveness of the Canadian experience. With growing pressures to take a North American view of Canadian policies it is vitally important that the differences delineated in this book are understood, not just for their urban policy implications but for broader purposes as well.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh1 aMercer, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe G